review_blob:
A truly great Lambic Gueuze and a wonderful introduction to this fascinating style. Refreshingly sour (but not too sour compared to a few other Lambics).
A very fruity nose and a long after taste. My favorite beer for this unique style.
The best dry and crispy, yet flowery pils I know. the best in its style for craft beer lovers.
A truly great Porter! Strong black appearance, Dark brown foam. The strong roasted barley taste is well balanced by a certain sweetness and the Oak Aromas (mainly Vanilla) are very well  noticed.

An interesting hazy Amber Ale, somewhere in between an American and an English Pale ale. a surprisingly full body to the ABV. very good balance between bitterness and sweetness and with a noticed fruity taste in the backround.
A great IPA! excellent for its style (the american version). a nice round palate with a full body and very long hoppy finish.
A very clean and natural blond beer with nothing really to talk about. plain simple, but a bit boring for a craft beer.
A crisp and fresh IPA with a very Hoppy nose. well balanced and not as much hoppy on tha palate and a nice long finish. Body could be a little fuller.

London Pride is the flagship English pale ale in my eyes.
Mild bitterness with certain fruity notes. a great introduction beer to this style.
This accurate lager was my first introduction to craft beer. The Hoppy aroma and well balanced bitterness/sweetness make it my first recommendation for any new comers to specialty beer.
